omer","HL454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748001","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-13","<p>The answer given on 21 March 2017 (HL6105) was in response to a question concerning safety improvements in the defence nuclear weapons programme. The response was in relation to radiological incidents at the Atomic Weapons Establishment (AWE), none of which have ever posed any risk to the health of the public or the environment. The incidents raised by the noble Baroness did occur; a small number of residents were evacuated in 2010 as a precautionary measure due to a fire in a non-nuclear area. I can confirm that in none of the incidents cited was it assessed that there was any radiological risk to the public.</p><p>The risk of any of these incidents recurring has been greatly reduced due to subsequent improvements to the infrastructure at AWE.</p><p>Activity at AWE sites is governed by a number of permits, authorisations, licences and consents for managing waste and discharges to the environment. AWE plc and the Ministry of Defence continuously monitor their compliance and inspections are routinely undertaken by the relevant regulatory authorities, including the Environment Agency.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL396 ; HL453 ; HL454","2017-07-13T14:42:35.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748001/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748001/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the risks to (1) the public, and (2) the environment, from the fire at the Atomic Weapons Establishment in August 2010.","false","Biography information for Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer",,"Baroness Miller of Chilthorne Domer","HL455"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748002","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Clean Air Zone Framework, published on 5 May 2017, sets out the principles local authorities should follow when setting up Clean Air Zones in England.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s consultation on the draft Air Quality Plan set out that charging zones should only be used where local authorities are unable to identify equally effective alternatives. It is for local authorities to develop local proposals likely to achieve the air quality limits within the shortest possible time, taking into consideration the effects and impacts on local residents and businesses.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s consultation closed on 15 June and responses to the consultation are currently being considered. The final Plan will be published by 31 July.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-18T10:41:51.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748002/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748002/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to encourage the introduction of charges in Clean Air Zones, with a view to discouraging the use of diesel cars in those zones.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748003","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-18","<p>In May, the Government published a consultation on the draft UK Air Quality Plan for tackling nitrogen dioxide. The consultation includes proposals for Clean Air Zones - designated geographical areas that provide a focus in some towns and cities to improve air quality by permitting vehicle access on the basis of emission standards.</p><p> </p><p>A range of potential measures were identified in the consultation including the introduction of a scrappage scheme. We are considering responses to the consultation. The final plan is due to be published by the 31 July 2017.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-18T10:42:19.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748003/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748003/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they have made an assessment of the potential impact of a diesel scrappage scheme on reducing levels of outdoor air pollution.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL457"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748004","Department of Health","false","2017-07-11","<p>We expect to publish the Government’s response to the National Data Guardian’s review of data security, consent and opt-outs and the Care Quality Commission’s review <em>Safe data, safe care</em> shortly. This will provide information to the National Health Service and adult social care on sharing data in lawful, safe and secure ways. In addition we intend to publish summary guidance in the autumn on the current regulatory framework for NHS trusts and suppliers.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-07-11T15:06:37.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748004/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748004/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the ruling by the Information Commissioner's Office on 3 July that the transfer of patient data from the Royal Free NHS Foundation Trust to DeepMind was illegal, what guidance they will give to NHS trusts regarding the sharing of patient data.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748005","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Department for Transport ran a public consultation about possible changes related to the testing of vehicles of historic interest, with a preferred option to move from the current position of an exemption for pre-1960 vehicles to a rolling 40 year exemption for vehicles which have not been substantially modified. There were more than 2,200 responses, including many from users and owners of historic vehicles. These responses are currently being considered and we hope to announce a response to this consultation later this year.</p><p> </p><p>An initial impact assessment was prepared which assessed that there were about 192,000 pre-1960 registered vehicles which are currently exempt from the MOT requirement. The preferred option identified in the consultation exempted an estimated further 278,000 vehicles. A final validated impact assessment will be published along with the consultation response summary.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-12T11:43:08.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748005/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748005/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether, before creating any new category of road vehicles of historic interest, they will engage in consultation with representatives of the estimated 250,000 users of such vehicles; and how many such vehicles they estimate to exist.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748006","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-12","<p>A consultation has been completed about exempting more vehicles of historic interest from testing, given an increased flexibility offered by changes in EU-wide standards, to which Sweden is also responding. The UK already exempts pre-1960 vehicles from testing and consideration is being given to changing that threshold, with a lead consultation option of exempting most vehicles more than 40 years old.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-12T11:43:45.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748006/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748006/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the decision by the government of Sweden to abolish testing for all road vehicles over 50 years old, what consideration they have given to applying a similar rule in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748007","Department for Education","false","2017-07-12","<p>Data on the number of children being educated at home are not collected centrally.</p><p>Parents have a legal duty under Section 7 of the Education Act 1996 to ensure that a child of compulsory school age receives an efficient and full-time education suitable to its age, ability and aptitude, and any special education needs - either by regular attendance at school or otherwise. ‘Otherwise’ includes education at home. There are no other specific requirements relating to the content of such education, unless a child has a statement of special educational needs or an Education and Health Care Plan, which can specify that the child is being educated at home. If it does, the local authority is under a duty to ensure the provision specified is made.</p><p>Parents choosing to educate at home take on the responsibilities involved, including financial responsibility. There is no entitlement to support. Some local authorities offer guidance, and there are other organisations which offer guidance or provide part-time education in specific subjects to supplement home education.</p>",,"Lord Nash","HL462","2017-07-12T11:56:08.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748007/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748007/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748007/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government how many children and young people have undertaken home tuition in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748008","Department for Education","false","2017-07-12","<p>Data on the number of children being educated at home are not collected centrally.</p><p>Parents have a legal duty under Section 7 of the Education Act 1996 to ensure that a child of compulsory school age receives an efficient and full-time education suitable to its age, ability and aptitude, and any special education needs - either by regular attendance at school or otherwise. ‘Otherwise’ includes education at home. There are no other specific requirements relating to the content of such education, unless a child has a statement of special educational needs or an Education and Health Care Plan, which can specify that the child is being educated at home. If it does, the local authority is under a duty to ensure the provision specified is made.</p><p>Parents choosing to educate at home take on the responsibilities involved, including financial responsibility. There is no entitlement to support. Some local authorities offer guidance, and there are other organisations which offer guidance or provide part-time education in specific subjects to supplement home education.</p>",,"Lord Nash","HL461","2017-07-12T11:56:08.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748008/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748008/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748008/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what are the legal requirements relating to home tuition; and what measures are in place to support parents who choose to have their children taught at home.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748009","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-18","<p>We are unable to confirm the position at a UK level as fisheries protection is a devolved matter. However, the Royal Navy Fishery Protection Squadron comprises of 3 offshore patrol vessels of which one is currently tasked to meet the contractual commitment to the Marine Management Organisation (MMO) for the purposes of fisheries enforcement in England.</p><p> </p><p>The number of RN Offshore Patrol Vessels reflects the adoption of a risk based, intelligence led operational model that enables targeted enforcement interventions in the right place at the right time. The requirement for all vessels over 12 metres in length to be fitted with the satellite tracking devices (Vessel Monitoring System) gives a real time picture of where fishing activity is happening enabling the efficient employment of patrol vessels. This information is monitored at the MMO control room in Newcastle.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, when the RN Offshore Patrol Vessels are at sea but conducting other tasks they are still able to provide a presence which has a deterrent effect. This is supplemented by joint working with other agencies such as Inshore Fisheries Conservation Authorities (IFCAs), UK Border Force (UKBF) and the Police to ensure effective and timely intervention where illegal activity is suspected. Radar sweeps can be used by patrol vessels to identify potential targets and the AIS (Automatic Identification System) is also used in fisheries enforcement to detect fishing activity, including where fishing vessels are operating.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-07-18T16:53:20.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748009/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748009/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748009/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government how many Fishery Protection ships are patrolling UK waters at any one time; and what is the total number in the squadron.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748010","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-17","<p>We have been clear that we want to give citizens and business in the UK and the EU, and from around the world, as much certainty as possible, as early as possible. This is why we want to have reached agreement about our future partnership by the end of March 2019. From that point on, we believe a phased period of implementation, during which time both Britain and the EU Institutions and Member States prepare for the new relationship, will help both sides to minimise unnecessary disruption.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-07-17T16:17:41.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748010/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748010/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748010/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to seek early agreement on a transition period for Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748011","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-11","<p>As the Chancellor has said, ultimately the location of the European Union’s agencies will be for the European Union.</p><p>In the negotiations the Government will discuss with the EU and Member States how best to continue to cooperate in the field of medicines and banking regulation in the best interests of both the UK and EU.</p><p><strong>Attachment: Jeremy Hunt, Secretary of State for Health and Greg Clark, Secretary of State for business <a href="https://www.ft.com/content/a94326ac-5dbd-11e7-9bc8-8055f264aa8b?mhq5j=e1" target="_blank">Financial Times letter</a> </strong></p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-07-11T13:01:18.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748011/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748011/answer","Hunt & Clark FT letter .pdf","Hunt and Clark FT letter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748011/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they intend that London-based EU agencies should remain located within the UK following Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748012","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-07-10","<p>Our aim is to ensure people can broadly live their lives as they do now. At every step of negotiations we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for UK Citizens. We are proposing a reciprocal deal which is fair and serious, and we are approaching these negotiations constructively and respectfully, with a determination to secure a deal that works for both the UK and the EU.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-07-10T13:51:56.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748012/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748012/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748012/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-07-04","EU Citizenship","2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to negotiate to enable UK citizens to keep their EU citizenship and rights following Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748013","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-18","<p>When the UK leaves the EU it will automatically become an independent coastal state. It will have rights to manage access to its waters and to work with other Coastal States, including the EU, to manage shared stocks and agree shares of fishing opportunities. The UK is already responsible for fisheries enforcement matters within its Exclusive Economic Zone.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-07-18T16:53:43.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748013/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748013/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748013/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the benefits, costs and risks of instituting an exclusive economic zone around the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748014","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-11","<p>The government believes that balancing the public finances is key to ensuring confidence in the UK economy and delivering sustainable growth. The Industrial Strategy will support economic growth by increasing productivity and driving growth across the whole country. The government has announced over £23bn of additional investment in economic infrastructure, research and development, and housing. The government will also cut corporation tax to 17 per cent - the lowest rate in the G20.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-07-11T15:10:02.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748014/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748014/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748014/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what measures have they put in place to ensure that investors have confidence in the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL468"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748015","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-07-17","<p>The class of substances known as Endocrine disruptors (EDCs) which include oestrogens found in contraceptive pills are a hazard to some wildlife. While it is correct that EDCs are a recognised environmental issue, which continues to be researched with a view to the protection of wildlife, EDCs do not pose a threat to drinking water supplies as drinking water treatment facilities will remove oestrogens, if they were to occur in river water.</p><p>The Environment Agency is currently commissioning work to survey the incidence and severity of intersex in wild fish in a number of rivers that were surveyed 15 years ago, to assess how the situation may have changed.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2017-07-17T12:43:04.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748015/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748015/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748015/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the findings of Professor Tyler of Exeter University relating to transgender fish in rivers affected by residues of contraceptive pills, what action they intend to take to avoid health risks to humans.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL469"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748016","Home Office","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Government is very concerned about the use of acid and other corrosives in violent attacks. The Government and the National Police Chiefs’ Council jointly hosted a meeting on 4 July with medical experts, police officers, retailers, and officials from a number of Government departments and agencies to share understanding about the nature of such attacks and discussed action being taken by the respective agencies. We are currently considering what further action can be taken to ensure public safety.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-18T11:30:28.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748016/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748016/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748016/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, in the light of figures released by the MPS showing an increase in the number of acid attacks in London from 261 in 2015 to 454 in 2016, what action they are taking to ensure public safety.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748017","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>There is no recognised term or a specific offence of “acid violence”. However, a range of offences are relevant depending on the nature of the violence and the harm caused.</p><p>The most serious violence and harm caused by use of acid or other corrosive substances is likely to be subject to section 18 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861 causes grievous bodily harm with intent to do so. This carries a maximum life sentence. In addition, someone who has possession of acid or other corrosive substances with an intention to do harm, is likely to be considered to be in possession of an offensive weapon, which is a criminal offence.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-17T11:32:56.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748017/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748017/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748017/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether acid violence is a recognised term within the criminal justice system; and if so, what is its definition.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748018","Home Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Home Office are working closely with a range of partners and agencies to consider the response to acid attacks including what advice is needed for individuals and medical practitioners to respond to these incidents. On 4 July, the Home Office and the National Police Chief’s Council jointly hosted a meeting with medical experts, police, retailers, and officials from a number of Government departments and agencies to share understanding about the nature of attacks and discussed action being taken by the respective agencies.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-20T15:20:45.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748018/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748018/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748018/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they are considering a public safety awareness campaign of the danger of acid attacks; and what advice is being given to individuals and emergency services to minimise long-term physical deformity.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748019","Department of Health","false","2017-07-11","<p>Emergency medical technicians and paramedics operate to the Joint Royal Colleges Ambulance Liaison Committee Clinical Practise Guidelines 2016. This does not refer to the use of Diphoterine. Ambulance personnel would follow the chemical, biological, radiological and nuclear advice in the guidelines to disrobe the patient and decontaminate with water.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL475","2017-07-11T15:01:51.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748019/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748019/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748019/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government how they ensure that, in responding to acid attacks, first responders are adequately equipped to deal with (1) the immediate effects, and (2) the need to prevent prolonged physical damage.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748020","Home Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>We are working closely with the National Police Chiefs’ Council lead on the scale and nature of attacks with acid and other corrosive substances and how to respond to such attacks.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-11T12:59:47.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748020/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748020/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748020/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to put in place a protocol with police, local authorities, and other emergency services, to respond to acid attacks.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL474"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748021","Department of Health","false","2017-07-11","<p>Emergency medical technicians and paramedics operate to the Joint Royal Colleges Ambulance Liaison Committee Clinical Practise Guidelines 2016. This does not refer to the use of Diphoterine. Ambulance personnel would follow the chemical, biological, radiological and nuclear advice in the guidelines to disrobe the patient and decontaminate with water.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy","HL473","2017-07-11T15:01:51.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748021/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748021/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748021/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether NHS protocols for the management of acid attacks include the use of Diphotrine for the purposes of emergency treatment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Uddin",,"Baroness Uddin","HL475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748022","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>We have not made any representations to the Spanish government on this issue. The UK is clear that questions related to Catalonia are a matter for the Government and people of Spain, and there needs to be respect for the laws and Constitution of Spain. As for UK citizens in Catalonia, they enjoy the same constitutional rights as UK citizens in any other autonomous community of the Kingdom of Spain.</p>",,"Baroness Goldie",,"2017-07-19T10:56:58.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748022/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748022/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748022/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they have made any representations to the government of Spain concerning judicial independence in Spain in relation to the rights of citizens in Catalonia, including those who also have UK citizenship.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748023","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>UK consulates are located in the following locations in the EU, outside capitals:</p><p><strong>CROATIA</strong></p><p>British Consulate Split</p><p><strong>FRANCE</strong></p><p>British Consulate Bordeaux</p><p>British Consulate Marseille</p><p><strong>GERMANY</strong></p><p>British Consulate General Dusseldorf</p><p>British Consulate General Munich</p><p><strong>GREECE</strong></p><p>British Vice Consulate Corfu</p><p>British Vice Consulate Crete</p><p>British Vice Consulate Rhodes</p><p>British Honorary Vice Consulate Zakynthos</p><p><strong>ITALY</strong></p><p>British Consulate General Milan</p><p><strong>NETHERLANDS</strong></p><p>British Consulate General Amsterdam</p><p><strong>PORTUGAL</strong></p><p>British Vice Consulate Portimão</p><p><strong>SPAIN</strong></p><p>British Consulate Alicante</p><p>British Consulate General Barcelona</p><p>British Consulate Malaga</p><p>British Consulate Ibiza</p><p>British Consulate Las Palmas de Gran Canaria</p><p>British Consulate Palma de Mallorca</p><p>British Consulate Santa Cruz de Tenerife</p><p>British Consulate, Bilbao</p>",,"Baroness Goldie",,"2017-07-19T10:55:51.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748023/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748023/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748023/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government in which cities within the EU, other than capital cities, UK consulates are located.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748024","Home Office","false","2017-07-17","<p>Home Office Ministers have met with a number of senior police leaders since the General Election on a wide range of issues including resources.</p><p> </p><p>We have protected overall police spending and Counter-Terrorism policing in real terms since Spending Review 2015.Every Police &amp; Crime Commissioner who maximised their local precept income in 2016-17 and 2017-18 is receiving at least the same direct resource funding in cash than they received in 2015-16.</p><p>We have a constructive and ongoing dialogue with policing about ensuring that the right powers, capabilities and resources are in place to keep t he public safe.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-17T11:25:55.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748024/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748024/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748024/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what discussions they have held with police commissioners about the adequacy of available resources for those commissioners to fulfil their role and duties.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748025","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-18","<p>The information requested could be provided only at disproportionate cost as central records are not kept for all aspects of the management of prisoners sentenced to an indeterminate sentence of Imprisonment for Public Protection (IPP).</p><p> </p><p>HM Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) and the Parole Board will continue to work together to improve the progression of IPP prisoners. This group continue to achieve release in high numbers, with 576 first time IPP releases in 2016, the highest figure since the sentence was introduced.</p><p> </p><p>HMPPS will continue to invest in interventions to assist prisoners to both reduce their risk and demonstrate such progression to the Parole Board. However, it is important to remember that it is not mandatory for IPPs to complete accredited offending behaviour programmes in order to achieve release. Completing an accredited offending behaviour programme is one way in which IPP prisoners may demonstrate that they have reduced their risk of harm and reoffending; other options may include work and employment, education and one to one work with psychologists or prison offender supervisors.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-07-18T16:25:18.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748025/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748025/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748025/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government during the last 12 months, how many prisoners sentenced to an indeterminate sentence of Imprisonment for Public Protection were (1) offered places on a training course which could lead to their release, (2) were released following completion of such training courses, and (3) refused to take up a place or dropped out of such courses; and how those figures compare with those for the preceding 12 month period.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748026","Department of Health","false","2017-07-18","<p>Appropriate staffing levels are already a core element of the Care Quality Commission’s (CQC’s) registration regime underpinned by legislation. All providers of regulated activities must be registered with the CQC and meet the registration requirements. The 16 safety and quality requirements set out in the Health and Social Care Act 2008 (Regulated Activities) Regulations 2014 include a requirement for the deployment of sufficient numbers of suitably qualified, competent, skilled and experienced persons.</p><p> </p><p>In July 2016, the National Quality Board published <em>Supporting NHS providers to deliver the right staff, with the right skills, in the right place at the right time: Safe, sustainable and productive staffing</em>. This safe staffing improvement resource provides an updated set of expectations for nursing and midwifery care staffing, to help National Health Service provider boards make local decisions that will support the delivery of high quality care for patients within the available staffing resource.</p><p> </p><p>A copy of <em>Supporting NHS providers to deliver the right staff, with the right skills, in the right place at the right time: Safe, sustainable and productive staffing</em> is attached.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>We now have 13,100 more nurses on our wards than in 2010.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-07-18T10:45:53.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748026/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748026/answer","nqb-guidance.pdf","Supporting NHS providers guidance","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748026/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-04",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what plans they have to introduce in England legislation analogous to the Nurse Staffing Levels (Wales) Act 2016 to make provision for safe nurse staffing levels in hospitals in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748033","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-13","<p>As announced in the Queens Speech on 21 June, the Government will bring forward legislation to tackle the continuing high number and cost of whiplash claims by:</p><ul><li>introducing a fixed tariff of compensation for pain, suffering and loss of amenity for whiplash claims with a duration of up to two years; and</li><li>banning the practice of seeking or offering to settle whiplash claims without medical evidence.</li></ul><p>These measures will be supported by further secondary legislative changes to the Civil Procedure Rules to increase the small claims track limit for road traffic accident related personal injury claims to £5,000, and for all other personal injury claims to £2,000.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-13T15:40:10.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748033/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748033/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748033/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-04","Personal Injury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to change regulations covering insurance claims for whiplash.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","2875"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748034","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government's manifesto re-affirms the commitment to deliver equal and updated boundaries and reduce the size of the House of Commons.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Following laws already passed by Parliament that set out the date of the electoral register to be used at boundary reviews, and provide that the current Boundary Review should be based on the electoral registers from 2015, the independent and impartial Boundary Commissions are consulting on their proposals to deliver the boundary changes, and they will submit their final proposals to Parliament in autumn 2018. These reforms will ensure fair and equal representation for the voting public across the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p>Equalising the size of constituencies in the Boundary Review will ensure everyone’s vote will carry equal weight. Without such boundary reforms, MPs could end up representing constituencies based on data that is over 20 years’ old, disregarding significant changes in demographics, house building and migration.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-10T16:27:29.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748034/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748034/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748034/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Constituencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make it his policy to use the June 2017 electoral registration figures to inform a future boundary review.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","2943"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748035","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>Cabinet Office has a whistleblowing policy and procedure in place which allows for civil servants to report a perceived wrongdoing within the department, including something that they believe goes against the core values in the Civil Service Code. The Public Interest Disclosure Act 1998 (PIDA) will apply in some of these cases, and provides protection to those that ‘blow the whistle’ in certain circumstances.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The figures provided in the table below show the total number of whistleblowing cases that were protected disclosures under PIDA (A).</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The table goes on to show the number of cases found to be valid under PIDA (B), the number of employees that alleged detriment as a result of the disclosure under PIDA (C), and finally the number of employees who made a disclosure under PIDA, alleged detriment as a result of a disclosure and subsequently left the department (D).</p><p><strong><p><p></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>A. Number of whistleblowing cases that were covered under PIDA</p></td><td><p>B. Number of cases found to be valid under PIDA</p></td><td><p>C. Number of employees that alleged detriment as a result of the disclosure under PIDA</p></td><td><p>D. Number of employees who subsequently left the department (i.e. after making a disclosure and then alleged detriment as a result of the disclosure)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>No data available</p></td><td><p>No data available</p></td><td><p>No data available</p></td><td><p>No data available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-11T15:47:48.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748035/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748035/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748035/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Cabinet Office: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many protected disclosures were made by staff in his Department in each of the last three years for which figures are available; how many such disclosures were found to be valid; how many staff alleged detriment as a result of making such a disclosure; and how many staff who (a) made such a disclosure and (b) alleged detriment as a result of a disclosure subsequently left the employment of the Department.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","2826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748036","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>All public authorities are required to implement government guidelines that set out how government buyers should source steel for major projects so that the true value of UK steel is taken into account in major procurement decisions.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-12T15:15:55.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748036/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748036/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Government Departments: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the level of Government procurement of UK steel was for each Department in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","2695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748037","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>I refer the Honourable gentleman to my previous answer (1204)</p><p>The Government published a draft Public Service Ombudsman Bill in December 2016, setting out in detail its plans to introduce a new Public Service Ombudsman. The draft Bill will be progressed as and when a legislative opportunity arises.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-11T14:07:46.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748037/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748037/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Public Service: Ombudsman","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what plans his Department has to introduce a single public service ombudsman.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","2733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748038","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government's manifesto re-affirms the commitment to deliver equal and updated boundaries and reduce the size of the House of Commons.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The progress of the current boundary review, which is proceeding in accordance with the laws already passed by Parliament, is a matter for the independent and impartial Boundary Commissions. Further information can be found on the websites for each of the four Boundary Commissions.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","2730","2017-07-10T16:29:28.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748038/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748038/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Constituencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Constituency Boundary Review is on track to report by 1 October 2018.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","2734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748039","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>In line with its manifesto commitment, the Government intends to legislate to ensure that a form of identification must be presented before voting. It is intended that this requirement be tested through pilot schemes at the May 2018 elections. Pilots will help to identify the best way of administering this new requirement.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government is continuing to work with the Law Commission on how best to implement the recommendations of their review of electoral law in collaboration with other stakeholders. We will respond to their report in due course.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","2731","2017-07-10T16:26:12.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748039/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748039/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Polling Stations: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make it his policy to introduce a requirement for voters to produce personal identification at a polling station to receive a ballot paper.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","2735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748040","Home Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>All Fire and Rescue Services plan for major and complex incidents. For multiple large scale incidents, if a fire and rescue service’s local capacity needs augmenting, there are well developed mutual aid arrangements so it can draw on resources from neighbouring fire and rescue services and across the country. Home Office supports specialist national resilience capabilities to respond to multiple scale incidents.</p><p> </p><p>The National Fire Chiefs Council (NFCC) provide the coordination of support for national level incidents, working closely with the Government crisis management structures.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","2726","2017-07-11T12:52:16.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748040/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748040/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-04","Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government has made of the capacity of the Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service to handle multiple large-scale incidents such as that at Grenfell Tower simultaneously.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748041","Home Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>All Fire and Rescue Services plan for major and complex incidents. For multiple large scale incidents, if a fire and rescue service’s local capacity needs augmenting, there are well developed mutual aid arrangements so it can draw on resources from neighbouring fire and rescue services and across the country. Home Office supports specialist national resilience capabilities to respond to multiple scale incidents.</p><p> </p><p>The National Fire Chiefs Council (NFCC) provide the coordination of support for national level incidents, working closely with the Government crisis management structures.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","2725","2017-07-11T12:52:16.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748041/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748041/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-04","London Fire and Emergency Planning Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government has made of the capacity of the London Fire Brigade to handle multiple large-scale incidents such as that at Grenfell Tower simultaneously.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748042","Home Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Home Office keeps the UK’s preparedness for terrorist attack under constant review, and is delivering a £144 million programme to increase numbers of armed police officers in the UK. The first phase of the armed uplift is complete, with an additional 41 Armed Response Vehicles and around 650 armed officers trained. The number of armed response vehicles has more than doubled in London and around a quarter of the national CTSFO capability will also be based in the capital.</p><p>The Home Office also trains and equips specialist fire and ambulance teams to manage casualties in higher risk environments. These capabilities are deployable to a terrorist incident occurring anywhere in the UK, including London. Police’s response to the Borough Markey attack was fast and effective, with at least six armed response vehicles arriving on scene within the first ten minutes.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-07-12T16:42:11.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748042/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748042/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-04","Metropolitan Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government has made of the capacity of the Metropolitan Police to handle multiple large-scale terrorist attacks such as that at Borough Market simultaneously.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748043","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government's manifesto re-affirms the commitment to deliver equal and updated boundaries and reduce the size of the House of Commons.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The progress of the current boundary review, which is proceeding in accordance with the laws already passed by Parliament, is a matter for the independent and impartial Boundary Commissions. Further information can be found on the websites for each of the four Boundary Commissions.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","2734","2017-07-10T16:29:28.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748043/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748043/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Constituencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether it remains Government policy to reduce the number of parliamentary constituencies to 600.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","2730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748044","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>In line with its manifesto commitment, the Government intends to legislate to ensure that a form of identification must be presented before voting. It is intended that this requirement be tested through pilot schemes at the May 2018 elections. Pilots will help to identify the best way of administering this new requirement.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government is continuing to work with the Law Commission on how best to implement the recommendations of their review of electoral law in collaboration with other stakeholders. We will respond to their report in due course.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","2735","2017-07-10T16:26:12.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748044/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748044/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when his Department plans to respond to the Law Commission's 2016 review of electoral law.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","2731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748045","Home Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Home Office keeps the UK’s preparedness for terrorist attack under constant review, and is delivering a £144 million programme to increase numbers of armed police officers in the UK. The first phase of the armed uplift is complete, with an additional 41 Armed Response Vehicles and around 650 armed officers. The next phase - an increase in Counter-Terrorism Specialist Firearms Officers - is expected to complete in 2018, with a proportion to be based in Manchester.</p><p>The Home Office also trains and equips specialist fire and ambulance teams to manage casualties in higher risk environments. These capabilities are deployable to a terrorist incident occurring anywhere in the UK, including in Greater Manchester. The emergency services’ response to the recent terrorist attack in Manchester was fast and effective, with at least six armed response vehicles arriving at the incident within ten minutes.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-07-12T16:41:26.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748045/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748045/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-04","Greater Manchester Police","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government has made of the capacity of Greater Manchester Police to handle multiple large-scale terrorist attacks simultaneously.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","2723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748046","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>Cabinet Office is committed to ensuring that the needs of Welsh language speakers are recognised and met.<a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank"> GOV.UK</a> gives every central government organisation the ability to publish content in Welsh.</p><p><strong><br></strong>There are currently more than 2,000 Welsh-language pages on<a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank"> GOV.UK</a>, an increase of over 50 percent in the past 12 months.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-10T16:17:20.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748046/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748046/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Electronic Government: Welsh Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps he is taking to ensure that all content on the gov.uk website is accessible to Welsh language users.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","2917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748047","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-24","<p>In 2014-15, Central Government spent over £12 billion (27.1%) with small and medium sized businesses, which shows a continued year on year increase in SMEs winning public procurements. The Manifesto committed to ensuring of 33% of spend with SMEs by the end of this Parliament.</p><p>Information on all public sector suppliers within a specific constituency is not held centrally.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-24T15:32:32.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748047/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748047/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Small Businesses: Arfon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the (a) amount and (b) proportion of public procurement spent by the Government placed with small and medium-sized enterprises in the Arfon constituency in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","2918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748048","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>Government departments are accountable for the provision of their services in the Welsh language, guided by the requirements of their individual Welsh Language schemes. Each department has its own system for understanding the need to translate services, for example whether they accept translation requests from the public.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-10T16:16:16.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748048/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748048/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Government Departments: Welsh Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which Government services are only available in the Welsh language on request.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","2919"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748049","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>We are committed to ensuring that the needs of Welsh language speakers are recognised and met. The Government Digital Service is working together with Wales Office to understand how high-quality online user journeys can best be provided to Welsh-language speakers.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","2921","2017-07-10T16:18:31.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748049/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748049/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Government Departments: Welsh Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing a right to equality of service for Welsh language users of Government digital services.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","2920"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748050","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-10","<p>We are committed to ensuring that the needs of Welsh language speakers are recognised and met. The Government Digital Service is working together with Wales Office to understand how high-quality online user journeys can best be provided to Welsh-language speakers.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","2920","2017-07-10T16:18:31.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748050/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748050/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Government Departments: Welsh Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of providing all Government digital services in the Welsh language in addition to English.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","2921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748051","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Red Tape Challenge was launched under the Coalition Government in 2011. The initiative ran until March 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Following the 2015 General Election, the Government continued the focus on improving regulation and established the Cutting Red Tape programme. In November 2016, policy responsibility moved from the Cabinet Office to the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-11T12:08:14.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748051/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748051/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 29 June 2017 to Question 861, on regulation, for what reason funds from the public purse were spent on the Red Tape Challenge in 2016-17 after the programme closed in 2015.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","2982"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748052","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>All 18 central government departments already offer Payroll Giving to their staff.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-12T11:29:17.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748052/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748052/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-04","Government Departments: Payroll Deduction Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government intends to introduce payroll giving as an option for all government staff.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748053","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-12","<p>According to the latest provisional statistics released by HM Revenue &amp; Customs (HMRC), fuel duties raised £27.9bn in the 2016-17 tax year. Forecasts for fuel duty revenues in future years are provided by the independent Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) in their ‘Economic and Fiscal Outlook’. For the latest fuel duty revenue forecast, please see Table 4.6 on page 104:</p><p><a href="http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/efo/economic-fiscal-outlook-march-2017/" target="_blank">http://budgetresponsibility.org.uk/efo/economic-fiscal-outlook-march-2017/</a></p><p> </p><p>The OBR do not publish forecasts of tax receipts past the five-year ‘scorecard’ period (currently ending in 2021-22). However, in their 2014 ‘Fiscal Sustainability Report’ they did assess the sustainability of fuel duty revenues over a longer period. Please see Chapter 4 (page 123) of the report for more information:</p><p><a href="http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/41298-OBR-accessible.pdf" target="_blank">http://cdn.budgetresponsibility.org.uk/41298-OBR-accessible.pdf</a></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-07-12T10:04:38.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748053/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748053/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Excise Duties: Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of how much will be raised for the public purse in fuel duty in each year to 2029-30.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","2961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748054","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-12","<p>The amount of funding available in the next round of Libor funding for charities (LIBOR 2017) will be confirmed once all applications for funding support have been received. The application window closes on 25 August 2017; full details of the scheme and the application form can be found at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/libor-funding-applications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/libor-funding-applications</a></p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-07-12T13:59:47.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748054/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748054/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","LIBOR: Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much funding will be available in the next round of Libor funding for charities.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748055","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-10","<p>Air ambulance charities, like most organisations and individuals, are required to pay VAT on their taxable purchases. The VAT refund scheme allows air ambulance charities to receive refunds of VAT.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-07-10T08:57:08.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748055/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748055/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","VAT: Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether air ambulance charities are required to pay VAT on their purchases.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","2979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748056","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-12","<p>UK banks’ and building societies’ treatment of their customers is governed by the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) in its Principles of Business. This includes a general requirement for firms to provide a prompt, efficient and fair service to all of their customers, including those who have recently suffered a bereavement.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is supportive of industry efforts to improve handling of these sensitive cases, including the implementation of the British Bankers’ Association’s Bereavement Principles. These Principles commit firms to support customers and, in particular, allow necessary payments to be made from the deceased’s accounts. Such payments include inheritance tax, which can be paid directly to HM Revenue and Customs, before probate is granted, through the Direct Payment Scheme. Where lower amounts are held, the Principles also commit firms to consider whether they can waive probate requirements and release funds more quickly.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-12T12:39:47.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748056/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748056/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Inheritance Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to encourage more financial institutions, including those based overseas, to provide support to executors and administrators of estates, including with regard to making the deceased's liquid assets available for the payment of inheritance tax prior to the grant of probate in line with the 2016 Bereavement Principles.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","2724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748057","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government has shown it is committed to reducing geographical, wealth and generational inequality. It will continue to consider such issues when making public spending allocations.</p><p> </p><p>A key priority for this government is to make sure the economy works for the whole country, not just certain parts. In the latest year, the economy grew fastest in the North West, the number of people in work grew fastest in the South West and unemployment fell fastest in Scotland. Looking ahead, the Government is developing an industrial strategy to drive productivity, create jobs, and ensure sustainable economic growth across the country.</p><p> </p><p>Our increases to the National Minimum Wage rate will benefit younger people, as will our actions to help young people get on the housing ladder. Income inequality is now lower now than it was in 2010, and the share of total income tax paid by the top 1% is 27%.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-07-10T14:54:14.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748057/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748057/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he plans to take in allocating public spending priorities in budgets during the course of the current Parliament to reduce (a) geographical, (b) wealth and (c) generational inequalities.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","2747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748058","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-12","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could be provided only at disproportionate cost. The exchequer impact of individual policy measures are estimated in HM Treasury’s publications on policy costings accompanying each fiscal event.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-12T08:33:53.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748058/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748058/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the value of tax cuts for companies and individuals earning more than £75,000 for each year since 2010 up to 2020.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","2742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748059","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-10","<p>The latest data shows median household financial debt in the North West is the second lowest of any English region.</p><p> </p><p>In the UK as a whole, household debt-to-income has increased marginally from 141% 12 months ago to 145% in Q1 2017. This remains significantly below the pre-crisis peak of 160% in Q1 2008.</p><p> </p><p>The independent Financial Policy Committee (FPC) was set up by the government to assess and mitigate financial stability risks, including from household debt. The FPC has taken action to ensure against a significant rise in highly indebted households.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-10T15:45:02.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748059/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748059/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the levels of household debt in the (a) Borough of Rochdale and (b) UK in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","2789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748060","Department for Education","false","2017-07-10","<p>The process required to sell part of the English student loan book under the Sale of Student Loans Act (2008) was launched in February this year. An update will be provided in due course.</p><p> </p><p>A sale on the basis set out in February would not represent a step towards privatisation of the provision or administration of student loans. The position of people with student loans would not be affected as a result of such a sale.</p><p>The proposed sale comprised the rights to future repayments and would not involve alteration of the mechanisms or terms of repayment.</p><p> </p><p>This sale process was the first in a planned programme of sales of loans issued under the previous “pre-2012” system, targeting £12bn of proceeds by the end of the 2020-21 financial year.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","2700","2017-07-10T15:40:40.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748060/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748060/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-04","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of potential revenue to be raised from the privatisation of the student loans book.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","2699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748061","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-11","<p>In its Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 69488, the Government stated that it was conducting research on the effects of transparency in overseas money transfers (involving foreign exchange) on consumer decisions. This research will help to inform the Government's response to the consultation on draft regulations for the implementation of the Second Payment Services Directive. This response will be published shortly.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-11T14:57:20.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748061/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748061/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Foreign Exchange: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Answer of 18 April 2017 to Question 69488, whether the results of research into the impact of pricing structures on consumer understanding of foreign currency transaction fees will inform forthcoming payment services regulations.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bowie","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Andrew Bowie","2823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748062","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-12","<p>The government legislated in the 2016 Finance Act to reduce the corporation tax rate to 17% in April 2020.</p><p> </p><p>We want to ensure the UK remains an attractive destination to set up and grow a business. Cutting corporation tax increases the returns companies receive on their investments, allowing them to increase investment, lower prices, hire staff or increase wages.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-12T09:19:46.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748062/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748062/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Corporation Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if the Government plans to bring corporation tax down to 17 per cent by 2020.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748063","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-11","<p>No protected disclosures were made in HM Treasury during this period.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-07-11T14:46:07.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748063/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748063/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Treasury: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many protected disclosures were made by staff in his Department in each of the last three years for which figures are available; how many such disclosures were found to be valid; how many staff alleged detriment as a result of making such a disclosure; and how many staff who (a) made such a disclosure and (b) alleged detriment as a result of a disclosure subsequently left the employment of the Department.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","2839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748064","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-12","<ol><li><p>Corporation tax liabilities for each business sector are published online here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/corporation-tax-payable-after-set-offs-classified-by-industry-by-year-of-liability" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/corporation-tax-payable-after-set-offs-classified-by-industry-by-year-of-liability</a>.</p><p> </p></li><li><p>Value Added Tax (VAT) liabilities for each business sector are published in the VAT Factsheet, which can be found on the following website under ‘Factsheet Datasets’: <a href="https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx" target="_blank">https://www.uktradeinfo.com/Statistics/Pages/TaxAndDutybulletins.aspx</a>. Tab 2.5 shows the net VAT declared on traders' returns classified by Trade Sub-Sector.</p></li></ol><p> </p><ol><li><p>The information requested on business rates receipts is not available.</p></li></ol><p> </p><ol><li><p>Robust estimates of national insurance contributions for each business sector are not available.</p></li></ol>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-12T08:35:33.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748064/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748064/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Taxation: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will set out total receipts for (a) corporation tax, (b) VAT, (c) business rates and (d) national insurance contributions for each business sector in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liam Byrne","Birmingham, Hodge Hill","Liam Byrne","2843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748065","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>Business rates are based on valuations from the Valuation Office Agency and we do not intervene in their independent assessments. We have put in place a £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme for England to support ratepayers at the 2017 revaluation. The transitional relief scheme has capped annual increases in rate bills due to the revaluation.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-14T17:43:59.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748065/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748065/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Non-domestic Rates: Solar Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of maintaining the previous lower level of business rates for roof-top solar.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","2844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748066","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer keeps all taxes, including alcohol duties, under review and considers a wide range of tax policy options before each Budget.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-07-10T08:58:47.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748066/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748066/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Excise Duties: Beer","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he estimated the cost of freezing beer duty for 2017-18 prior to the introduction of the Spring Budget 2017.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","2852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748067","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Chancellor keeps all taxes under review as part of the on-going Budget process.</p><p> </p><p>Consistent with the government’s tax consultation framework, where possible, the Government will engage interested parties on changes to tax policy and legislation at each key stage of developing and implementing the policy.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-07-12T16:05:59.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748067/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748067/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Excise Duties: Diesel Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans he has to undertake a consultation exercise on vehicle excise duty for new diesel vehicles.","false","Biography information for Mr William Wragg","Hazel Grove","Mr William Wragg","2879"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748068","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-11","<p>Where Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding is present on social housing over 18 metres in height, the Government is providing testing for local authorities and housing associations free of charge. If the screening tests indicate that such cladding would not meet the limited combustibility requirements of the current Building Regulations guidance, local authorities, housing associations and the fire and rescue service will determine the best course of action, communicating closely with residents. Where work is necessary to ensure the fire safety of social housing, we will ensure that lack of financial resources will not prevent it going ahead.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-11T09:31:27.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748068/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748068/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748068/answer/previousversion/3138","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","High Rise Flats: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what funding and other support his Department has offered to Manchester City Council to carry out fire safety checks on high-rise buildings.","false","Biography information for Jeff Smith","Manchester, Withington","Jeff Smith","2948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748069","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-12","<p>The department has not received any protected disclosures in the last three years.</p><p>In recent years the department has improved its strategic leadership and accountability of whistleblowing and improved whistleblower support. We have a senior whistleblowing champion with overall responsibility for whistleblowing practices and have implemented a</p><p>clear and transparent policy and provided comprehensive guidance for staff. We also have a central point of contact for staff to raise concerns which is staffed by whistleblowing nominated officers who have received specialist training on how to respond to any concerns</p><p>raised.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-12T16:30:42.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748069/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748069/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Department for Communities and Local Government: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many protected disclosures were made by staff in his Department in each of the last three years for which figures are available; how many such disclosures were found to be valid; how many staff alleged detriment as a result of making such a disclosure; and how many staff who (a) made such a disclosure and (b) alleged detriment as a result of a disclosure subsequently left the employment of the Department.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","2827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748070","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-06","<p>Two codes of management practice, approved by the Secretary of State in June 2016, for the residential leasehold sector already exist. These codes set out the law and best practice, and can be used in evidence in Court or tribunal proceedings.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-06T15:09:33.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748070/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748070/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Housing: Freehold","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of regulations governing the level of management fees which can be charged to freeholders of new build properties.","false","Biography information for Lucy Allan","Telford","Lucy Allan","2797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748071","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-11","<p>An update to the costings for the Help to Buy: ISA can be found in the supporting documents to the Autumn Statement 2016. The expected cost of the government bonus payments through the Help to Buy: ISA is £1.2 billion from 2016-17 to 2019-20.</p><p>The expected cost of government bonus payments through the Lifetime ISA is as follows:</p><p>£170m in 2017/18</p><p>£330m in 2018/19</p><p>£580m in 2019/20</p><p>£830m in 2020/21</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-11T14:55:27.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748071/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748071/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748071/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the projected annual cost is of bonuses due to holders of Help-to-Buy and Lifetime ISAs for each financial year from 2017-18 onwards.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748072","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-11","<p>Across England there are 173 social housing buildings that are over 18 metres tall and clad with some form of Aluminium Composite Material (ACM). Systems that failed the Government’s large scale cladding tests are in use on 165. Cladding systems that passed the tests are in use on eight social housing towers. As each test was completed the Government contacted the owners of all affected buildings to share detailed advice drawn up by the Independent Expert Advisory Panel. This covers steps to ensure the safety of residents including, where necessary, removal of cladding.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-11T15:26:30.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748072/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748072/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748072/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will list the cases where samples of exterior cladding have failed the combustibility test commissioned by his Department; and in which of those cases the cladding (a) needs to be removed and (b) can remain in place.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748073","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Government is determined that insurers should treat customers fairly and firms are required to do so under the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) rules. The FCA sets the conduct standards required of insurance firms which aim to ensure consumers are treated fairly.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor has discussed the Grenfell tower disaster with leading industry representatives to get an understanding of how they may respond, and any possible impact on insurance for residents. The industry have said that it is too early to properly understand the implications, so have not yet made any changes to their underwriting models or pricing strategies.</p><p> </p><p>The Treasury has also been in contact with leading insurance companies and has received assurances that no individuals in tower blocks have been refused access to home insurance as a result of the fire at Grenfell Tower. Officials remain in regular contact with the insurance industry to understand how it may shape their view of fire risk. The Treasury will continue to monitor the situation and will investigate this matter further if it sees evidence of customers in tower blocks being treated unfairly.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-11T15:01:00.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748073/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748073/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-04","House Insurance: High Rise Flats","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the insurance industry after the Grenfell Tower fire to ensure that residents of other tower blocks (a) can take out building or contents insurance and (b) do not pay more as a result of the fire at Grenfell Tower.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748074","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government is committed to working with places to generate growth and jobs. This is not a one-size-fits-all process; for example, mayoral governance may be appropriate for cities but not rural counties. We will continue to work with Devon and Somerset to ensure they have the tools to drive growth.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-07-10T15:15:36.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748074/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748074/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Devolution: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress has been made on devolution for Devon and Somerset.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","2694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748075","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Government has not set a date for the permanent rehousing of those who lost their homes, but we are working rapidly to find permanent housing as soon as possible. We have already announced a new block of social housing in Kensington Row that will provide 68 permanent new homes, and we are urgently working with a number of developers to secure similar properties in the area. The Prime Minister said clearly in her statement on 22 June that families who lost their homes as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire will be guaranteed a new home on the same terms as the one they lost. We are working closely with the families to ensure the properties made available will match what they want.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T16:38:03.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748075/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748075/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, by what date everyone who lost their home as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire will be permanently rehoused.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748076","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-28","<p>Following the tragedy at Grenfell Tower, we will need to consider the position on guidance further alongside the Prime Minister's commitment to look at wider issues.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-28T09:21:09.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748076/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748076/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748076/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Building Regulations: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish any research or work commissioned in preparation for the revision of Approved Document B of the Building Regulations.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2714"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748077","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Prime Minister said clearly in her statement on 22 June that families who lost their homes as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire will be guaranteed a new home on the same terms as the one they lost. We are working closely with the families to ensure the properties made available will match what they want.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T16:56:16.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748077/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748077/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748077/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will guarantee that no resident who lost their home as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire will be rehoused in a property where they (a) pay a higher rent or (b) have less security of tenure.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748078","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-19","<p>On 30 June, we published a note at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing</a> that sets out the immediate steps providers of social housing should be taking to ensure fire safety following the identification of Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding. It is for the building owner to consider whether to remove cladding. They should take expert professional advice on this. Removal of cladding needs to be done safely and without compromising other aspects of the building’s external wall system.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-19T13:53:05.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748078/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748078/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Social Rented Housing: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his advice to councils and housing associations which are responsible for properties that have exterior cladding that has failed combustibility tests is to remove that cladding.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748079","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-11","<p>The estimate of 530 given on 3 July came from early work that looked at social housing clad in any sort of aluminium in England. We have since been in regular contact with every local authority and housing association in the country to identify all social housing tower blocks above 18 meters that are clad specifically in aluminium composite material (ACM). Based on work to date, we know there are 173 high rise social housing buildings with ACM cladding in England and that 165 of these buildings have cladding systems that present fire hazards. We are not currently aware of any other ACM clad social housing blocks that are awaiting testing.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-11T15:25:48.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748079/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748079/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, by what date he will ensure that all 530 tower blocks that have been identified as having aluminium composite material cladding will be tested.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748080","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-12","<p>It is important that everyone affected by this terrible tragedy gets all the support and help they need.</p><p>Anyone who wishes to undertake a search of the probate registry papers, or to obtain copies of a Will or grant of probate, may make an application to the relevant Probate Registry. The fee of £10 also includes a copy of the grant of probate (if one has been made) and the Will (if there is one).</p><p>The Lord Chancellor has a power to remit fees where there are exceptional circumstances for doing so. Anyone who wishes to make an application for a fee remission should contact the delivery manager at the Probate Registry.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-07-12T14:29:54.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748080/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748080/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748080/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-04","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what support the Government is able to provide for Grenfell Tower residents to access Probate Registry papers.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","2791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748081","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-10","<p>As of noon on Wednesday 5 July 2017, 117 households who have permanently lost their homes as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire had received one or more payments from the Grenfell Tower Residents’ Discretionary Fund. The Council has made contact with a further 8 households understood to have lost their homes, and is proactively working to seek out and contact any remaining households that are yet to come forward through the key workers team.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-10T16:31:42.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748081/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748081/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people who lost their homes as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire have yet to receive any discretionary payments from the Grenfell Tower Residents' Discretionary Fund.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748082","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-10","<p>158 families from Grenfell Tower and Grenfell Walk have been identified in need of temporary housing. Offers of appropriate and good quality temporary accommodation have been made to all 139 households who are ready and able to talk to the housing team. As of 5 July, 14 offers of temporary accommodation have been accepted, and 3 families have already moved in. We have already announced a new block of social housing in Kensington Row that will very shortly provide 68 new permanent homes, and we are urgently working with a number of developers to secure similar properties in the same area.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-10T16:30:00.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748082/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748082/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748082/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people who lost their homes as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire have yet to be given (a) temporary and (b) permanent accommodation.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748083","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Government has acted on the recommendations of the Coroner's report into the Lakanal House fire. In relation to the recommendation to simplify the fire safety guidance relating to Building Regulations (Approved Document B), this work was being progressed. Following the tragedy at Grenfell Tower, we will need to consider the position on guidance further alongside the Prime Minister's commitment to look at wider issues. This work will now need to be informed by any recommendations that the independent inquiry into the Grenfell Tower fire make.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-13T15:38:48.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748083/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748083/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748083/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748083/answer/previousversion/3137","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, with reference to the letter of 28 March 2013 from Judge Kirkham to the then Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government on the conclusion of the Lakanal House fire inquest, what progress his Department has made in supporting the implementation of each of the Coroners' recommendations as set out in that letter.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748084","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-10","<p>All residents should understand the emergency fire safety guidance in their buildings. It is for local authorities and other housing providers to ensure that this is the case.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-10T16:26:22.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748084/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748084/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748084/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ensure that emergency guidance in high rise blocks is available in a variety of languages to cater for the diversity of the residents in those blocks.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","2770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748085","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-10","<p>Every family that is ready to talk to the housing team has been offered a temporary home. As of 5 July, 139 families have received offers of accommodation. 19 families have not yet been ready to engage in this process, and we need to respect that and go at the pace that they want to. The housing team will continue to work with all families to ensure that their individual needs are met.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-10T16:30:59.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748085/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748085/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748085/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many residents who lost their home as a result of the Grenfell Tower fire have not received an offer of housing.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748086","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government committed to make an offer of temporary housing to all those who have lost their homes as a result of the fire, within three weeks. All 139 of the families who are ready to talk to the housing team have already been matched with and offered a quality, appropriate temporary home. All these homes are local - either in Kensington and Chelsea or a neighbouring borough.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-10T16:33:40.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748086/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748086/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748086/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on ensuring that the survivors of the Grenfell Tower fire of 17 June 2017 are rehoused nearby within three weeks.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","2755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748087","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-06","<p>Kensington and Chelsea Tenant Management Organisation (KCTMO) was established in 1996, taking over management responsibilities for 9,760 properties from the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea.</p><p>The Government does not hold information on KCTMO’s management agreement with the local authority, including any agreements between KCTMO and the local authority regarding the sub-contracting of any housing functions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-06T15:11:40.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748087/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748087/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748087/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Social Rented Housing: Kensington and Chelsea Borough Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information he holds on what housing functions in Kensington and Chelsea Council have been contracted to the private sector; and when each such function was so contracted.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","2741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748088","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-11","<p>Where work is necessary to ensure the fire safety of social housing, we will ensure that lack of financial resources will not prevent it going ahead.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-11T09:26:36.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748088/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748088/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748088/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748088/answer/previousversion/3142","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of removing and reapplying cladding from tower blocks that have failed safety checks on the housing reserves of social landlords that acquired those tower blocks through stock transfer.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","2992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748089","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-10","<p>The tests currently being carried out are focussed on the combustibility of material in cladding made from Aluminium Composite Material. Where those materials have failed that test, housing providers have had instructions to review all fire safety arrangements in the relevant property, and to check insulation and other materials in the wall construction. Where work is necessary to ensure the fire safety of social housing, we will ensure that lack of financial resources will not prevent it going ahead.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-10T16:27:26.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748089/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748089/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much financial support his Department will provide to local authorities for assessing the fire safety of insulation.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","2993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748090","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department has compiled information on buildings of interest, including all residential tower blocks over 18 metres owned by local authorities and housing associations. We continue to strengthen this information, working closely with tower block owners. Information on the constituency is recorded where independent Building Research Establishment tests have been failed. Local authorities have been asked to contact relevant constituency MPs.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-11T09:48:56.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748090/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748090/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748090/answer/previousversion/3140","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","High Rise Flats: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has a central database of all residential tower blocks, including information by (a) type of tower block owner, (b) local authority and (c) constituency.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","2981"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748092","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>Where Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding is present on residential buildings over 18 metres in height, the Government is providing testing for local authorities, housing associations and private sector landlords, free of charge. If the screening tests indicate that such cladding would not meet the limited combustibility requirements of the current Building Regulations guidance, it is for landlords in consultation with the fire and rescue service and other experts to determine, and take, the best course of action, communicating closely with residents. My Department has issued advice on the interim mitigating measures landlords should implement. Where work is necessary to ensure the fire safety of social housing, we will ensure that lack of financial resources will not prevent them going ahead.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-14T11:06:43.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748092/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748092/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748092/answer/previousversion/3141","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-04","Fire Prevention: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what funding is available to (a) local authorities, (b) arms-length management organisations, (c) social landlords whose properties have been acquired through stock transfer and (d) private landlords for the (i) removal of cladding that has failed safety tests and (ii) reapplication of new cladding.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","2991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748093","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>Boards of trustees allow charities across the country to improve lives and address some of the most significant challenges we face.</p><p>The Government has been working with the Charity Commission and voluntary sector partners, to carry out research to understand the current makeup of trustees and to identify ways to further strengthen trusteeship.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-10T16:33:21.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748093/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748093/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748093/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Charitable Trusts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps her Department is taking to promote charity trusteeship, particularly to those from disadvantaged backgrounds.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748094","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Fundraising Regulator has said that it is on track to raise at least £1.8m from its voluntary levy for the year September 2016 to August 2017. Almost all of the largest fundraising charities have paid the levy. Some smaller fundraising charities have yet to respond and a few have refused to pay. The Fundraising Regulator is continuing to chase these charities. It will be for the Fundraising Regulator to decide whether to publish the names of those charities that have refused to pay or that have not responded to payment requests.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-11T15:32:54.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748094/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748094/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748094/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Charitable Donations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent estimate she has made of the amount raised by the Fundraising Regulator's levy on charity fundraising in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2957"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748095","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-12","<p>Swimming is both an important sport and physical activity, and a key life skill. I am very happy to meet with Swim England and British Swimming, in addition to meetings I already have planned with Swim England’s Swim Group, to discuss increasing participation in swimming for fitness and competitive swimming.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-12T11:34:27.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748095/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748095/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748095/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Swimming: Public Participation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether (a) she and (b) the Minister for Sport plan to meet (i) Swim England and (ii) British Swimming to discuss increasing participation in (A) swimming for fitness and (B) competitive swimming.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748096","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-11","<p>The levy enables the Fundraising Regulator to strengthen the Code of Fundraising Practice, resolve public complaints and concerns about fundraising, and ultimately supports public trust and confidence in fundraising.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-11T15:35:11.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748096/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748096/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748096/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Charitable Donations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of the Fundraising Regulator's levy on charity fundraising.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2956"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748097","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-12","<p>We have not been approached about this issue and no recent discussion has taken place. Sport England is currently in discussions with National Disability Sports Organisations, about the role they can play to support the delivery of Government's strategy for sport and physical activity, Sporting Future, which is focused on tackling inactivity in priority groups, such as disabled people. This includes discussions with Special Olympics GB and Mencap about the work that they do with people with disabilities.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-12T10:09:23.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748097/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748097/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748097/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Sports Competitors: Down's Syndrome","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions her Department has had with disability sports organisations on classing Down's syndrome athletes as a separate and discreet class and excluding such athletes from participation opportunities in national disability sports events.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","2938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748098","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Government’s latest research found that 46% of UK businesses identified a cyber security breach or attack in the past 12 months. This includes 45% among micro and small businesses, 66% among medium businesses and 68% among large businesses.</p><p> </p><p>Further details can be found in the 2017 Cyber Security Breaches Survey:</p><p><br> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/cyber-security-breaches-survey-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/cyber-security-breaches-survey-2017</a></p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-10T12:48:39.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748098/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748098/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748098/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Cybercrime: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment she has made of the number of cyber security breaches businesses have incurred in the last 12 months; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","2754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748099","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>Government is committed to building the resilience and independence of smaller charities. In recognition of this, the Office for Civil Society in England are providing a multi-year programme of fundraising training and support. The aim is to help small, local charities build their fundraising skills, knowledge and confidence through face-to-face training, intensive one-to-one advice sessions, skilled volunteering matches and webinars. The training will be provided at little or no cost and the providers will also develop and share fundraising training resources and toolkits to support small charities who might not be able to attend training.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-10T16:36:43.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748099/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748099/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Charities: Fund Raising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what support her Department provides to small charities for fundraising training; and if she will increase the level of such support given.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748100","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>Government is committed to supporting small charities to become more independent, resilient and sustainable. Examples of recent work include the announcement of a further three years of the Small Charities Fundraising Training Programme, our Local Sustainability Fund for small to medium sized organisations and work to explore the role of small charities in public services. The Government will continue to support small charities and will work with the sector to develop plans.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-10T16:20:49.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748100/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748100/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department has produced a long-term plan on providing support to build the capacity and resilience of smaller charities.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","2698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748101","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>The private sector plays an important role in helping people who do not have computers to access products and services. DCMS is working with industry to ensure consumers have this access, as set out in the UK Digital Strategy.</p><p> </p><p>Many large corporates pledged practical support in the Strategy, which was launched by the Secretary of State in March this year. This includes more than 4 million digital skills training opportunities, which will be delivered through the newly established Digital Skills Partnership.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-10T12:52:46.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748101/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748101/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Electronic Commerce: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with large companies on ensuring that people who do not have computers are not disadvantaged when accessing services or products; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","2817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748102","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>As announced in the Queen's Speech, we will put forward proposals for a Digital Charter which will set out a framework for how businesses, individuals and wider society should act online. This will ensure we get the right balance between freedom and security in the digital age, so that we can harness the power of new technology for good, and mitigate the new threats it presents.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-10T12:50:57.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748102/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748102/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Digital Technology: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what her policy is on bringing forward a Digital Charter.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","2821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748103","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>Local Charities Day in 2016 was successful and demonstrated to small, local charities how that Government values the important work they do. The Government is committed to continuing to recognise and support small local charities and an announcement on plans will be made in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-10T16:31:14.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748103/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748103/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748103/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Charities: Festivals and Special Occasions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what plans she has to hold a second local charities day; and if she will make it an annual event.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748104","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>In February 2017, the Civil Society Implementation Group, chaired by Sir Martyn Lewis, was formed. It was tasked with creating delivery proposals for policies related to public services and civil society, including the Incubator. The group has met on 15 separate occasions and Government is considering its proposals.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-10T16:24:24.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748104/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748104/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Public Sector: Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how often the public services programme implementation group, announced on 13 December 2016 has met; and what progress has been made in developing a Public Service Incubator.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748105","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sports is committed to ensuring the Information Commissioner's Office (ICO) is adequately resourced to fulfil its new responsibilities under the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which includes guidance and support to businesses. The ICO has issued guidance for businesses including charities on how to prepare for the GDPR. This is available at: <a href="https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/data-protection-reform/guidance-what-to-expect-and-when/" target="_blank">https://ico.org.uk/for-organisations/data-protection-reform/guidance-what-to-expect-and-when/</a>. In addition, the Fundraising Regulator has published specific guidance for fundraising charities available at: <a href="https://www.fundraisingregulator.org.uk/information-registration-for-fundraisers/guidance/personal-information-fundraising-consent-purpose-transparency/" target="_blank">https://www.fundraisingregulator.org.uk/information-registration-for-fundraisers/guidance/personal-information-fundraising-consent-purpose-transparency/</a></p><p>Both organisations continue to engage with charities to raise awareness.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-10T16:42:31.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748105/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748105/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Charities: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what support her Department is providing to charities to help them prepare for the implementation of the General Data Protection Regulation.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748106","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-11","<p>Government is committed to building the resilience and independence of smaller charities. Through our ongoing dialogue across the sector, we know that small charities want more support to fundraise effectively through better use of digital technology.</p><p>In recognition of this, the Office for Civil Society in England are providing a multi-year programme of fundraising training and support. This includes expert support to build the digital fundraising capabilities of small charities through face-to-face training, intensive one-to-one advice sessions, skilled volunteering matches and webinars.</p><p>The training will be provided at little or no cost and the providers will also develop and share fundraising training resources and toolkits to support small charities who might not be able to attend training.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-11T10:14:09.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748106/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748106/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748106/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Charities: Fund Raising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what support her Department is providing to charities to help them adopt digital technology for fundraising.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748107","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p><br> The Government is committed to the Public Services (Social Value) Act, which can unlock a range of public benefits from the procurement of goods and services. An announcement on Government's plans in relation to the Act will be made in due course.</p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-10T16:22:20.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748107/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748107/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Public Services (Social Value) Act 2012","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what progress has been made on the review of the Public Services (Social Value) Act 2012 announced on 8 February 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","2814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748108","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-12","<p>None.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-07-12T16:32:34.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748108/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748108/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, how many protected disclosures were made by staff in her Department in each of the last three years for which figures are available; how many such disclosures were found to be valid; how many staff alleged detriment as a result of making such a disclosure; and how many staff who (a) made such a disclosure and (b) alleged detriment as a result of a disclosure subsequently left the employment of the Department.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","2828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748109","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-12","<p>Sport England is the body responsible for making investment decisions on grassroots sports facilities in England.</p><p> </p><p>Across London, Sport England is currently investing £3.8 million from the Strategic Facilities Fund to construct three new leisure facilities which include swimming pools. It does not currently have any plans to fund the construction of a new swimming pool in Hornsey and Wood Green, but is able to offer support and guidance on how additional funding and advice could be accessed.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Local Government is by far the largest investor into community sport with £1bn invested each year and most grassroots sport is played using facilities (including parks and informal spaces) owned or controlled by the 353 local authorities in England. The government, through Sport England, works in partnership with local authorities to maximise the impact of this investment and safeguard it within the tough economic climate in which we all operate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Sports policy is devolved and therefore the investment in swimming pools in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland is a matter for the devolved governments and Sport Wales, Sport Scotland and Sport Northern Ireland respectively.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-12T14:42:46.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748109/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748109/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Swimming Pools: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department plans to provide funding for the construction of new swimming pools in (a) Hornsey and Wood Green, (b) London and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748110","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>Sport England is the body responsible for supporting and investing in grassroots and community sport.</p><p> </p><p>Between 2017 and 2021 Sport England is investing £12.16 million in Swim England, the national governing body for the sport, to get more people swimming, to support local clubs and to help talented swimmers to develop.</p><p> </p><p>This investment includes £4.6 million to support talented athletes on Swim England's swimming, synchronised swimming and water polo programmes.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-10T16:17:01.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748110/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748110/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Swimming: Clubs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to support local competitive swimming clubs.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748111","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-07-10","<p>Sporting Future set out the government's commitment to ensure that no child leaves primary school unable to swim and commissioned Swim England's Swim Group to undertake a review of how children could be better supported to meet this aim. <br></p><p>Sport England invests in a number of programmes and campaigns to encourage more adults to learn to swim. Between 2017 and 2021 Sport England is investing £12.16 million in Swim England to get more people swimming, support clubs and to help talented swimmers. This investment includes a social swimming project run by Swim England which is focused on helping adults learn to swim.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-07-10T16:18:51.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748111/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748111/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748111/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-07-04","Swimming: Public Participation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she is taking to (a) ensure that all children learn to swim and (b) encourage adults to learn to swim.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","2868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748112","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-10","<p>The Ministry of Defence takes the maintenance of Operational Advantage and Freedom of Action very seriously. Radar technology is a rapidly developing area and we are investing in technology developments in order to update our capabilities to meet emerging threats. In doing so we strive to meet the needs of our Armed Forces with responsible acquisitions that comply with our security and capability requirements. The development of an Active Electronic Scanned Array radar for Typhoon is an example of such investment.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-07-10T14:22:11.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748112/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748112/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748112/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-04","Radar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to support development of UK sovereign military radar capability.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2909"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748113","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-10","<p>Since the Strategic Defence and Security Review announcement, the UK missile defence community has been undertaking detailed scoping of the options for the future ground-based ballistic missile defence (BMD) radar. A Request For Information was issued to Industry in June this year to gather information about radar technology and capability. We expect the radar to be in service by the mid-2020s.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-07-10T14:17:17.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748113/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748113/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-04","Ballistic Missile Defence: Radar","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 4.16 of the National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, what progress has been made on his Department's plan to invest in a ground-based BMD radar.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748114","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-10","<p>RAF Henlow has been identified as having a Housing Unit potential for up-to 2,000 houses. The number of houses built on the site once sold is a matter for the future purchaser and the local Planning Authority.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-07-10T15:42:35.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748114/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748114/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-04","RAF Henlow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many homes he expects to be built on land currently owned by his Department at RAF Henlow in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748115","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-07-10","<p>Since the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, the UK has continued to explore the potential for the Type 45 Destroyers to operate in a ballistic missile defence role, including through active engagement with NATO partners.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-07-10T16:41:03.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748115/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748115/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748115/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-07-04","Type 45 Destroyers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to paragraph 4.16 of the National Security Strategy and Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, what recent representations his Department has received from NATO on the Government's commitment to investigate further the potential of the Type 45 destroyers to operate in a BMD role.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","2907"
